SIMPLE: outwit
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Outwit
<hw>Out*wit"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
surpass in wisdom, esp. in cunning.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To defeat or gain an advantage over by superior
craft or cunning stratagems; <as>as, the thief <ex>outwitted</ex> his
pursuers and left the country undetected</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>They did so much <qex>outwit</qex> and outwealth us !</q>
<rj><qau>Gauden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Outwit</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Outwit
<hw>Out"wit</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The faculty of
acquiring wisdom by observation and experience, or the wisdom so
acquired; -- opposed to <ant>inwit</ant>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Piers Plowman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Outwoe</ent>⟦br⟧
